will it work if I depoy to vercel and migrate to hosting services?

>>>

Yes, migrating to Vercel or other hosting services (like Netlify or GitHub Pages) will work perfectly with your monorepo architecture, but there is one critical technical reality: a hosted website cannot directly see your local computer files.Because your UI will now be "in the cloud" while your Obsidian vault is "on your hard drive," you need a bridge to keep them in sync.

🚀 The "Cloud-to-Local" Bridge StrategySince you are using a monorepo, here is exactly how to handle the data flow once you go live:1. The GitHub "Middleman" (Recommended)This is the most stable way to ensure your Vercel deployment and your local notes stay connected.Vercel watches your /planner-ui folder. Every time you push code, your website updates.Obsidian Git Plugin handles the data. You install this plugin inside Obsidian. It will "Pull" any changes made by the GitHub Project sync and "Push" your local notes back to the repo.Result: Your hosted planner and your local Obsidian app stay in sync by talking to the same GitHub repository.2. 
The Browser "Direct Save" (Local Bridge)If you want your hosted site to save files directly to your local vault without pushing to GitHub first, you can use the File System Access API.How it works: You add a "Connect Vault" button to your UI. When clicked, the browser asks you to select your local /obsidian-vault folder.Persistence: The browser "remembers" this permission for the session, allowing your hosted app to write .md files directly to your machine as if it were a local app.🛠️ Migration ChecklistStepActionWhy?Monorepo SplitSet Vercel's Root Directory to /planner-ui.Prevents Vercel from trying to "build" your Obsidian notes.API KeysAdd your GitHub Personal Access Token (PAT) to Vercel Environment Variables.Allows your sync engine to talk to your GitHub Project boards.CORS PolicyIf your planner makes API calls, ensure your hosting domain is whitelisted.Prevents "Cross-Origin" security blocks.
⚠️ A Note on SecurityWhen you move from local hosting (localhost) to a public URL (profound-planner.vercel.app), anyone with the link could potentially see your planner.Vercel Authentication: If you have a Pro account, you can enable Deployment Protection .Simple Fix: Add a basic password protection layer in your script.js that checks against an environment variable before rendering the planning data.

