To make this a "live" system where your hosted planner, GitHub, and local Obsidian vault act as one organism, you need a Three-Way Sync architecture.The goal: You change a task in the UI (hosted on Vercel) → GitHub updates → Your local Obsidian vault automatically pulls the change.

🏗️ The Live Bridge ArchitectureThe "Glue" is the GitHub Repository itself. It acts as the central database for both your code and your markdown files.1. The Monorepo Layouttext/ProfoundProjects-Suite (The GitHub Repo)
├── /planner-ui          # Hosted on Vercel (The "Remote Control")
└── /obsidian-vault      # Cloned to your local PC (The "Hard Drive")
    ├── .obsidian/
    ├── Daily/
    └── Projects/
Use o código com cuidado.
2. Phase One: Remote to Local (GitHub → PC)To get data from your hosted planner into your actual Obsidian app, you use the Obsidian Git Plugin.How it works: This plugin runs inside Obsidian on your computer.The "Live" Part: Set it to "Auto-pull" every X minutes.Result: When your hosted planner pushes a new note to GitHub, Obsidian "sees" it and downloads it automatically without you touching a button.
3. Phase Two: The API Bridge (Vercel → GitHub)Since your hosted UI (Vercel) cannot "touch" your local computer, it talks to the GitHub API instead.The Logic: Your script.js uses a GitHub Personal Access Token (stored securely in Vercel Environment Variables).The Action: When you hit "Save" on your hosted planner:The JS sends the data to GitHub's API.GitHub creates the .md file inside the /obsidian-vault/ folder in the repo.GitHub commits the change.
4. Phase Three: The GitHub Action (Automation)If you want GitHub Project Boards to also talk to Obsidian:The Script: A GitHub Action listens for "Card Moved" events.The Output: It automatically writes a Markdown file into the /obsidian-vault/ folder in the repository.The Loop: Since Obsidian is auto-pulling from the repo, your board movements appear in Obsidian as notes within minutes.
